OJECT FOR C$4.5 BLN]]></body>\n    </ArticleItem>\n    <ArticleItem id=\"1062942\">\n        <NewsType>In-depth</NewsType>\n        <NewsTypeID>NT02</NewsTypeID>\n        <Currencies>\n            <CurrencyID>SEK</CurrencyID>\n        </Currencies>\n        <NewsCategory><![CDATA[Commentary]]></NewsCategory>\n        <NewsCategoryID>NC-CT</NewsCategoryID>\n        <CurrencyPairs>\n            <FXPair>EUR/SEK</FXPair>\n        </CurrencyPairs>\n        <Country>Sweden</Country>\n        <Date>20180529</Date>\n        <TimeGMT>13:04</TimeGMT>\n        <Revision>0</Revision>\n        <Headline><![CDATA[Swedish economic sentiment falls in May, implies subdued domestic demand and higher inflation]]></Headline>\n        <Headline2><![CDATA[Swedish Economic Sentiment Falls In May, Implies Subdued Domestic Demand And Higher Inflation]]></Headline2>\n        <body><![CDATA[<p>The Swedish economic sentiment indicator continues to be at elevated levels in the month of May; however, the details imply subdued domestic demand and higher inflation going forward, noted Nordea Bank in a research report.<br>\n<br>\nThe overall sentiment in the Economy (ESI) dropped to 108.8 in May from 110.4, mainly because of softer confidence among consumers and declining sentiment in the construction sector.&nbsp; Consumer confidence index dropped further to 09.5 from 100.3. Manufacturing industry&rsquo;s sentiment index remained lofty, coming in at 118.6, as compared with the prior figure of 120.3, although production expectations dropped.<br>\n<br>\nSentiment for the construction industry took a hit, coming in at 104.3. Order book expectations continued to decline and are now below the 20-year average. Firms&rsquo; employment plans in the business sector continued to be largely unchanged, and are still at high levels compared to the average. But, the employment plans dropped in both the construction and manufacturing sector.<br>\n<br>\nHouseholds&rsquo; inflation expectations continued to be unchanged at 3.1 percent. According to the old method, expectations rebounded to 2.3 percent, the highest reading since mid-2012. Retailers&rsquo; price plans also rose markedly, probably because of a weak krona.<br>\n<br>\nOverall, the ESI indicator indicates a deceleration of growth. Households are less positive compared to a year ago, as well as the construction sector. In spite the ESI indicator being a poor indicator for overall growth the past year, the ESI indicator underpins the view of a weaker domestic demand going forward, stated Nordea Bank.<br>\n<br>\nFxWirePro launches Absolute Return Managed Program. For more details, visit&nbsp;<a>http://www.fxwirepro.com/invest</a></p>\n]]></body>\n    </ArticleItem>\n    <ArticleItem id=\"1062941\">\n        <NewsType>In-depth</NewsType>\n        <NewsTypeID>NT02</NewsTypeID>\n        <Currencies>\n            <CurrencyID>USD</CurrencyID>\n        </Currencies>\n        <NewsCategory><![CDATA[Commentary]]></NewsCategory>\n        <NewsCategoryID>NC-CT</NewsCategoryID>\n        <Country>United States</Country>\n        <Date>20180529</Date>\n        <TimeGMT>13:03</TimeGMT>\n        <Revision>0</Revision>\n        <Headline><![CDATA[Global geopolitical Series: Trump praises response to his letter as North Korea’s top man arrives in Washington to discuss meeting]]></Headline>\n        <Headline2><![CDATA[Global Geopolitical Series: Trump Praises Response To His Letter As North Korea’s Top Man Arrives In Washington To Discuss Meeting]]></Headline2>\n        <body><![CDATA[<p>In a tweet, the U.S. President praised the response from the North Korean side to his letter last week, where he officially canceled the meeting with North Korea&rsquo;s supreme leader Kim Jong-un scheduled for June 12th in Singapore. After Trump&rsquo;s open letter to Kim that was published by the White House, canceled the meeting citing tremendous anger and hostility from the North Korean side, a flurry of diplomatic efforts took place in order to secure the meeting. Top U.S. and South Korean diplomats met with their North Korean counterparts. South Korean president Moon Jae in himself met with Kim Jong-Un.</p>\n\n<p>Though President Trump hasn&rsquo;t officially revived the meeting, he praised the coming of former North Korean top military official Kim Jong Chol as the top negotiator to Washington. He wrote, <strong>&ldquo;We have put a great team together for our talks with North Korea. Meetings are currently taking place concerning Summit, and more. Kim Young Chol, the Vice Chairman of North Korea, heading now to New York. Solid response to my letter, thank you!&rdquo;</strong></p>\n]]></body>\n    </ArticleItem>\n    <ArticleItem id=\"1062940\">\n        <NewsType>Headline Only</NewsType>\n        <NewsTypeID>NT01</NewsTypeID>\n        <Currencies>\n            <CurrencyID>TRY</CurrencyID>\n        </Currencies>\n        <NewsCategory><![CDATA[Money Market]]></NewsCategory>\n        <NewsCategoryID>NC-MM</NewsCategoryID>\n        <CurrencyPairs>\n            <FXPair>USD/TRY</FXPair>\n        </CurrencyPairs>\n        <Country>Turkey</Country>\n        <Date>20180529</Date>\n        <TimeGMT>13:02</TimeGMT>\n        <Revision>0</Revision>\n        <Headline><![CDATA[TURKISH CENTRAL BANK SAYS OPENS $100 MLN 3-MONTH LIRA NDF SALE AUCTION]]></Headline>\n        <Headline2><![CDATA[Turkish Central Bank Says Opens $100 Mln 3-month Lira Ndf Sale Auction]]></Headline2>\n        <body><![CDATA[TURKISH CENTRAL BANK SAYS OPENS $100 MLN 3-MONTH LIRA NDF SALE AUCTION]]></body>\n    </ArticleItem>\n    <ArticleItem id=\"1062939\">\n        <NewsType>Headline Only</NewsType>\n        <NewsTypeID>NT01</NewsTypeID>\n        <Currencies>\n            <CurrencyID>TRY</CurrencyID>\n        </Currencies>\n        <NewsCategory><![CDATA[Money Market]]></NewsCategory>\n        <NewsCategoryID>NC-MM</NewsCategoryID>\n        <CurrencyPairs>\n            <FXPair>USD/TRY</FXPair>\n        </CurrencyPairs>\n        <Country>Turkey<